    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial statement excerpts, here are the detailed accounting policies regarding satellite manufacturing costs, capitalization criteria, and Property, Plant, and Equipment (PP&E):\n\n### 1. Satellite Manufacturing and Launch Costs\n*   **Cost Composition:** The capitalized cost of satellites includes direct manufacturing costs (parts, labor, and allocated overhead) as well as **capitalized launch costs** incurred by the Space segment to deploy the satellites into orbit. This includes an allocation of the flight vehicle\'s costs.\n*   **Inter-segment Launches (Starlink):** When the Space segment launches the company\'s own Starlink satellites, no inter-segment revenue is recognized. Instead, all associated launch costs are directly capitalized into the "Satellites" asset class within PP&E.\n*   **Inventory vs. PP&E:** While reusable components (boosters, fairings, engines, Dragon capsules) are classified as PP&E, non-reusable components (like Falcon 9/Heavy second stages) are recorded as **Inventory** and expensed to Cost of Revenue when launched or assigned to a mission. \n\n### 2. Capitalization Policies\n*   **Maintenance vs. Enhancements:** \n    *   *Expensed:* Routine maintenance and repairs that do not extend an asset\'s life are expensed as incurred.\n    *   *Capitalized:* Significant refurbishments, renewals, and enhancements that increase an asset\'s functionality, output, or expected life are capitalized and depreciated ratably over the newly identified useful life.\n*   **Interest Capitalization:** \n    *   The company capitalizes interest costs associated with significant, long-term construction projects (e.g., AI infrastructure data centers). \n    *   **Trigger & Calculation:** Capitalization begins when activities to prepare the asset for its intended use commence. It is calculated using the average accumulated expenditures multiplied by the company\'s weighted average borrowing rate (absent specific project borrowings).\n    *   **Cessation:** Capitalization stops for any portions of the project that are substantially completed and ready for use. Capitalized interest becomes part of the asset\'s historical cost and is depreciated over its useful life. *(Note: $169 million in interest was capitalized in 2025, primarily for AI data centers).*\n\n### 3. Property, Plant, and Equipment (PP&E)\n*   **Initial Measurement:** PP&E is stated at historical cost less accumulated depreciation.\n*   **Depreciation Methods:**\n    *   **Straight-Line:** Used for almost all asset classes (servers, machinery, data centers, buildings, etc.).\n    *   **Units of Production (Flights):** Flight vehicle hardware and spacecraft are depreciated based on the **expected number of average flights** rather than time.\n    *   **Leasehold Improvements:** Depreciated over the *shorter* of their estimated useful lives or the related lease term.\n\n#### Estimated Useful Lives & Critical Estimates\nManagement periodically reviews useful life estimates with engineering and operations teams. Key asset lives include:\n*   **Satellites (3 - 5 years):** \n    *   *Broadband satellites:* 5-year useful life.\n    *   *First-generation mobile satellites:* 3-year useful life.\n    *   *Factors considered:* Engineering studies, historical on-orbit performance, propellant life, utilization patterns, and planned transitions to newer tech.\n*   **Flight Vehicle Hardware (5 - 25 flights):** \n    *   *Factors considered:* Recovery/refurbishment success rates, economic feasibility of reflights, customer acceptance limits for reflown hardware, and anticipated retirement timing (e.g., transitioning from Falcon to Starship).\n*   **Other Notable Assets:** Servers/Networking (5-6 years), Data Center Infrastructure (20-25 years), Launch Sites (7-20 years), Buildings (30 years).\n\n#### Impairment Evaluation\n*   **Methodology:** PP&E is evaluated for impairment whenever events or circumstances indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable (e.g., technological obsolescence, damaged assets, negative industry trends). \n*   **Level of Assessment:** Assessed at the lowest level for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent of other assets.\n*   **Recognition:** If future cash flows are less than the carrying value, an impairment charge is recognized to write the asset down to its fair value. \n    *   *Example:* In 2025 and 2024, the company recorded impairments of $38M and $63M, respectively, related to damaged flight vehicles (Space segment) and damaged satellite hardware/abandoned production lines (Connectivity segment).\n*   **Sensitivity of Estimates:** Satellite useful life is a highly sensitive critical accounting estimate. Changing the average useful life of satellite assets by just **one year** would have impacted operating income by approximately **$480 million** for the full year 2025, and **$170 million** for the first quarter of 2026.',
