        output='Based on the provided financial statement excerpts, here are the critical accounting estimates and policies regarding research and development (R&D), software development (including internal-use software), and cost capitalization criteria:\n\n### 1. Research and Development (R&D) Costs\n*   **General Expensing Policy:** The Company expenses all R&D costs as they are incurred. These costs include materials, employee and contractor compensation, cloud computing, data services, equipment leases, R&D depreciation, and allocated overhead. It also includes engineering services for product features/modules where the Company retains the intellectual property.\n*   **Space Segment & Starship Development:** Space R&D is heavily focused on the development, build, and testing of Starship (including test flight hardware and Raptor engines). Because Starship is currently in the development stage, the majority of its costs are expensed to R&D as incurred. \n*   **Post-Commercialization Shift:** The Company expects R&D expenses to moderate once Starship is commercialized (defined as delivering payload to orbit). Upon commercialization, Starship costs will shift from being expensed to being **capitalized** and subsequently depreciated within the cost of revenue of the associated segment.\n\n### 2. Software Development and Internal-Use Software\n*   **On-Premise Software:** Software development costs marketed under on-premise perpetual licenses are expensed as R&D until technological feasibility is established. Because the Company\'s development cycle dictates that technological feasibility occurs shortly before general release, **all** software development costs for the years ended 2023, 2024, and 2025 were expensed as incurred.\n*   **Internal-Use Software (ASU 2025-06):** In September 2025, the FASB issued ASU No. 2025-06, which simplifies capitalization guidance for internal-use software by removing prescriptive and sequential "project stages" from ASC 350-40. The standard is effective for annual periods beginning after December 15, 2027. The Company is evaluating the update but does not expect a material impact on its consolidated financial statements.\n\n### 3. Cost Capitalization Criteria\n*   **Maintenance vs. Enhancements:** Routine maintenance and repairs that do not extend an asset\'s life are expensed as incurred. However, significant refurbishments, renewals, and enhancements that increase an asset\'s functionality, output, or expected life are **capitalized** and depreciated ratably over the identified useful life.\n*   **Satellites:** Capitalized satellite costs include build costs (parts, labor, allocated overhead) as well as launch costs incurred by the Space segment to deliver the satellites to orbit (including allocations for flight vehicle costs).\n*   **Interest Capitalization:** The Company capitalizes interest costs associated with the significant acquisition or construction of Property, Plant, and Equipment (PP&E). Capitalization begins when preparation activities commence and ceases when the asset (or portion thereof) is substantially completed and ready for its intended use. Capitalized interest is treated as part of the asset\'s historical cost.\n*   **Reusable Flight Hardware:** Boosters, fairings, Merlin/Raptor engines, and the Dragon capsule are classified as PP&E and capitalized, whereas non-reusable second stages are recorded as inventory until launch.\n\n### 4. Critical Accounting Estimates (Useful Lives & Depreciation)\nManagement must apply significant judgment to estimate the useful lives and depreciation methods for aerospace assets:\n*   **Flight Vehicles (e.g., Falcon 9 & Heavy):** Unlike standard PP&E (which uses straight-line depreciation), flight vehicles are depreciated based on the **expected number of average flights**. \n    *   *Estimation Criteria:* Management considers recovery/refurbishment success rates, refurbishment economics, customer acceptance limits for reflown hardware, and the mission manifest. \n    *   *Strategic Caps:* Although Falcon 9 boosters are engineered for up to 40 flights, the Company established a **maximum accounting useful life of 25 flights**. This estimate accounts for the strategic transition to Starship (which will reduce Falcon demand) and government contract restrictions prohibiting boosters flown more than five times.\n    *   *Sensitivity:* A change of +/- 5 average flights would *not* have a material impact on operating income.\n*   **Satellite Constellations:** Satellites are depreciated using the straight-line method based on engineering studies, propellant life, on-orbit performance, and planned technology transitions. \n    *   *Estimates:* Broadband satellites have a **5-year** useful life; first-generation mobile satellites have a **3-year** useful life.\n    *   *Sensitivity:* A 1-year change in the average useful life of satellite assets would impact operating income by approximately **$480 million** (for the year ended Dec 31, 2025) and **$170 million** (for the three months ended March 31, 2026).\n*   **Contract Margins (Cost-to-Cost Method):** For Space and Connectivity contracts recognized over time, management must estimate total costs at completion (factoring in launch timing, shared reusable vehicle costs, and technological changes). A 1% variance in the combined gross margins for these contracts would have impacted 2025 operating income by approximately **$110 million**.',
