**$2,000M** |\\n\\n$$\\\\Delta \\\\text{Segment Adj. EBITDA} = \\\\$0 - (-\\\\$2{,}000\\\\text{M}) = \\\\mathbf{\\\\$2{,}000\\\\text{M}} = \\\\mathbf{\\\\$2.00\\\\text{B}}$$\\n\\nThis result holds regardless of the assumed useful life or whether the satellites are placed in service during the year, because **all depreciation is added back** in the Segment Adjusted EBITDA reconciliation.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Disclosed Accounting Policies Governing the Judgment\\n\\nThe filing discloses **five interrelated accounting policies** that would govern whether these costs are capitalized or expensed:\\n\\n#### 1. R&D Expensing Policy (favors expensing)\\n> *\\"The Company expenses all R&D costs as they are incurred.\\"*\\n\\nR&D costs include materials, employee and contractor compensation, cloud computing, equipment leases, R&D depreciation, and allocated overhead. If orbital AI compute satellites are still in the development stage (deployment is not expected until **as early as 2028** per the filing), this policy would require immediate expensing of the $2B.\\n\\n#### 2. Starship Commercialization Precedent (the most directly analogous framework)\\nThe filing explicitly discloses that Starship — currently in the development stage — has the **majority of its costs expensed to R&D as incurred**. The company states:\\n\\n> *\\"The Company expects R&D expenses to moderate once Starship is commercialized (defined as delivering payload to orbit). Upon commercialization, Starship costs will shift from being expensed to being capitalized and subsequently depreciated within the cost of revenue of the associated segment.\\"*\\n\\nThis establishes a **bright-line commercialization milestone** precedent. By analogy, orbital AI compute satellite manufacturing costs would likely be expensed as R&D until a comparable commercialization threshold is met (e.g., successful deployment and operation of an orbital AI compute shell).\\n\\n#### 3. PP&E / Satellite Capitalization Policy (favors capitalization once production begins)\\n> *\\"Capitalized satellite costs include direct manufacturing costs (parts, labor, and allocated overhead) as well as capitalized launch costs incurred by the Space segment to deploy the satellites into orbit.\\"*\\n\\nOnce satellites transition from development to production, this policy governs capitalization. Satellites are depreciated straight-line over estimated useful lives of **3–5 years** (broadband satellites: 5 years; first-generation mobile satellites: 3 years). The filing notes that a 1-year change in satellite useful life would impact operating income by approximately **$480M** (FY2025), underscoring the materiality of this estimate.\\n\\n#### 4. Inter-Segment Cost Allocation Policy\\nThe filing discloses that when the Space segment launches the company\'s own satellites, **no inter-segment revenue is recognized**. Instead, all associated launch costs are directly capitalized into the \\"Satellites\\" asset class within the **end-user segment\'s** PP&E. The filing explicitly states:\\n\\n> *\\"The company expects to allocate a significant amount of future launch capacity (and the associated capitalized costs) to the AI segment to support the deployment of orbital AI compute/data center satellites.\\"*\\n\\nThis confirms that once capitalized, these costs would be borne by the **AI segment** (not the Space segment), directly impacting AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA.\\n\\n#### 5. Interest Capitalization Policy (ancillary)\\n> *\\"The Company capitalizes interest costs associated with significant, long-term construction projects (e.g., AI infrastructure data centers).\\"*\\n\\nCapitalization begins when preparation activities commence and ceases when the asset is substantially completed. The company capitalized **$169M** in interest in 2025, primarily for AI data centers. This policy could apply to orbital AI compute satellite construction if it qualifies as a significant long-term construction project, adding capitalized interest to the asset\'s cost basis.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Critical Judgment and Analytical Conclusion\\n\\nThe **central accounting judgment** is whether orbital AI compute satellite manufacturing costs are in the **development/R&D stage** (expensed under Policy 1, guided by the Starship precedent in Policy 2) or the **production/commercial stage** (capitalized under Policy 3).\\n\\nGiven that:\\n- The filing states orbital AI compute satellite deployment is not expected until **as early as 2028**\\n- The Starship precedent requires a **commercialization milestone** (payload to orbit) before capitalization begins\\n- The filing characterizes orbital AI compute as a \\"novel, untested technology\\" requiring \\"massive, multi-year capital expenditures before becoming profitable (if ever)\\"\\n\\n…the **R&D expensing policy and Starship commercialization precedent** would most likely govern in the near term, requiring the $2B to be expensed. This would reduce AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA by the full $2B compared to a capitalization treatment — a material difference given that the AI segment reported Segment Adjusted EBITDA of **$(1,237)M** in FY2025.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Sources\\n\\n{\\n  \\"sources\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)\\"\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}"}',
        parsed_args={
            'final_result': '## Difference in AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA: Capitalization vs. Expensing of $2B Orbital AI Compute Satellite Manufacturing Costs\n\n### Quantified Difference: **$2.00 Billion**\n\nThe capitalization treatment produces AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA that is **$2.00 billion higher** than the expensing treatment in the hypothetical year.\n\n---\n\n### Step-by-Step Calculation\n\n**Segment Adjusted EBITDA Formula (as disclosed):**\n\n> Segment Adjusted EBITDA = Income (Loss) from Operations\n> \\+ Depreciation & Amortization\n> \\+ Share-Based Compensation\n> \\+ Restructuring Charges\n> \\+ Impairment\n\n**Scenario A — Capitalization Treatment:**\n- The $2B in manufacturing costs is recorded as a PP&E asset (satellites) on the balance sheet.\n- If placed in service during the year, depreciation expense is recognized (e.g., $2B ÷ 5-year useful life = $400M annual depreciation), reducing operating income by that amount.\n- However, **depreciation is fully added back** in the Segment Adjusted EBITDA reconciliation.\n- Net impact on Segment Adjusted EBITDA = **$0** (depreciation reduces operating income but is added back dollar-for-dollar).\n- If not yet placed in service (still in Construction-in-Progress), no depreciation is recorded and there is zero P&L impact. Net impact = **$0**.\n\n**Scenario B — Expensing Treatment:**\n- The full $2B is immediately expensed to the income statement (likely as R&D expense).\n- Operating income is reduced by the full **$2B**.\n- This operating expense is **not** among the permitted add-backs (it is not D&A, SBC, restructuring, or impairment).\n- Net impact on Segment Adjusted EBITDA = **−$2B**.\n\n**Difference:**\n\n| | Capitalization | Expensing | Difference |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Operating Income Impact | $0 (or −depreciation) | −$2,000M | — |\n| D&A Add-back | +$0 (or +depreciation) | +$0 | — |\n| **Net Segment Adj. EBITDA Impact** | **$0** | **−$2,000M** | **$2,000M** |\n\n$$\\Delta \\text{Segment Adj. EBITDA} = \\$0 - (-\\$2{,}000\\text{M}) = \\mathbf{\\$2{,}000\\text{M}} = \\mathbf{\\$2.00\\text{B}}$$\n\nThis result holds regardless of the assumed useful life or whether the satellites are placed in service during the year, because **all depreciation is added back** in the Segment Adjusted EBITDA reconciliation.\n\n---\n\n### Disclosed Accounting Policies Governing the Judgment\n\nThe filing discloses **five interrelated accounting policies** that would govern whether these costs are capitalized or expensed:\n\n#### 1. R&D Expensing Policy (favors expensing)\n> *"The Company expenses all R&D costs as they are incurred."*\n\nR&D costs include materials, employee and contractor compensation, cloud computing, equipment leases, R&D depreciation, and allocated overhead. If orbital AI compute satellites are still in the development stage (deployment is not expected until **as early as 2028** per the filing), this policy would require immediate expensing of the $2B.\n\n#### 2. Starship Commercialization Precedent (the most directly analogous framework)\nThe filing explicitly discloses that Starship — currently in the development stage — has the **majority of its costs expensed to R&D as incurred**. The company states:\n\n> *"The Company expects R&D expenses to moderate once Starship is commercialized (defined as delivering payload to orbit). Upon commercialization, Starship costs will shift from being expensed to being capitalized and subsequently depreciated within the cost of revenue of the associated segment."*\n\nThis establishes a **bright-line commercialization milestone** precedent. By analogy, orbital AI compute satellite manufacturing costs would likely be expensed as R&D until a comparable commercialization threshold is met (e.g., successful deployment and operation of an orbital AI compute shell).\n\n#### 3. PP&E / Satellite Capitalization Policy (favors capitalization once production begins)\n> *"Capitalized satellite costs include direct manufacturing costs (parts, labor, and allocated overhead) as well as capitalized launch costs incurred by the Space segment to deploy the satellites into orbit."*\n\nOnce satellites transition from development to production, this policy governs capitalization. Satellites are depreciated straight-line over estimated useful lives of **3–5 years** (broadband satellites: 5 years; first-generation mobile satellites: 3 years). The filing notes that a 1-year change in satellite useful life would impact operating income by approximately **$480M** (FY2025), underscoring the materiality of this estimate.\n\n#### 4. Inter-Segment Cost Allocation Policy\nThe filing discloses that when the Space segment launches the company\'s own satellites, **no inter-segment revenue is recognized**. Instead, all associated launch costs are directly capitalized into the "Satellites" asset class within the **end-user segment\'s** PP&E. The filing explicitly states:\n\n> *"The company expects to allocate a significant amount of future launch capacity (and the associated capitalized costs) to the AI segment to support the deployment of orbital AI compute/data center satellites."*\n\nThis confirms that once capitalized, these costs would be borne by the **AI segment** (not the Space segment), directly impacting AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA.\n\n#### 5. Interest Capitalization Policy (ancillary)\n> *"The Company capitalizes interest costs associated with significant, long-term construction projects (e.g., AI infrastructure data centers)."*\n\nCapitalization begins when preparation activities commence and ceases when the asset is substantially completed. The company capitalized **$169M** in interest in 2025, primarily for AI data centers. This policy could apply to orbital AI compute satellite construction if it qualifies as a significant long-term construction project, adding capitalized interest to the asset\'s cost basis.\n\n---\n\n### Critical Judgment and Analytical Conclusion\n\nThe **central accounting judgment** is whether orbital AI compute satellite manufacturing costs are in the **development/R&D stage** (expensed under Policy 1, guided by the Starship precedent in Policy 2) or the **production/commercial stage** (capitalized under Policy 3).\n\nGiven that:\n- The filing states orbital AI compute satellite deployment is not expected until **as early as 2028**\n- The Starship precedent requires a **commercialization milestone** (payload to orbit) before capitalization begins\n- The filing characterizes orbital AI compute as a "novel, untested technology" requiring "massive, multi-year capital expenditures before becoming profitable (if ever)"\n\n…the **R&D expensing policy and Starship commercialization precedent** would most likely govern in the near term, requiring the $2B to be expensed. This would reduce AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA by the full $2B compared to a capitalization treatment — a material difference given that the AI segment reported Segment Adjusted EBITDA of **$(1,237)M** in FY2025.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
