bital AI compute satellite manufacturing costs are in the **development/R&D stage** (expensed under Policy 1, guided by the Starship precedent in Policy 2) or the **production/commercial stage** (capitalized under Policy 3).\n\nGiven that:\n- The filing states orbital AI compute satellite deployment is not expected until **as early as 2028**\n- The Starship precedent requires a **commercialization milestone** (payload to orbit) before capitalization begins\n- The filing characterizes orbital AI compute as a "novel, untested technology" requiring "massive, multi-year capital expenditures before becoming profitable (if ever)"\n\n…the **R&D expensing policy and Starship commercialization precedent** would most likely govern in the near term, requiring the $2B to be expensed. This would reduce AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA by the full $2B compared to a capitalization treatment — a material difference given that the AI segment reported Segment Adjusted EBITDA of **$(1,237)M** in FY2025.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
